  <section>
    <h2>Heading Scale</h2>
    <p>VB provides six heading levels, each mapped to a font-size token. All headings share <code>font-weight: 600</code>, <code>text-wrap: balance</code>, lining numerals, and disabled hyphenation.</p>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/headings-scale.html" url="https://vanilla-breeze.dev/headings/scale" title="Heading scale" shadow></browser-window>
    <code-block language="html" label="Heading scale">{{ scaleCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Element</th>
          <th>Font Size Token</th>
          <th>Computed</th>
          <th>Letter Spacing</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;h1&gt;</code></td>
          <td><code>--font-size-4xl</code></td>
          <td>2.25rem (36px)</td>
          <td><code>-0.025em</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;h2&gt;</code></td>
          <td><code>--font-size-3xl</code></td>
          <td>1.875rem (30px)</td>
          <td><code>-0.01em</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;h3&gt;</code></td>
          <td><code>--font-size-2xl</code></td>
          <td>1.5rem (24px)</td>
          <td>normal</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;h4&gt;</code></td>
          <td><code>--font-size-xl</code></td>
          <td>1.25rem (20px)</td>
          <td>normal</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;h5&gt;</code></td>
          <td><code>--font-size-lg</code></td>
          <td>1.125rem (18px)</td>
          <td>normal</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;h6&gt;</code></td>
          <td><code>--font-size-md</code></td>
          <td>1rem (16px)</td>
          <td>normal</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>h1 and h2 get tighter letter-spacing (tracking) because large text has more apparent whitespace between characters. h6 uses <code>font-weight: 700</code> instead of 600 for visual differentiation at body-text size.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Document Hierarchy</h2>
    <p>Headings create the document outline. Use them in order without skipping levels &mdash; an <code>&lt;h3&gt;</code> should always follow an <code>&lt;h2&gt;</code>, never an <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> directly.</p>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/headings-in-article.html" url="https://vanilla-breeze.dev/headings/hierarchy" title="Heading hierarchy in article" shadow></browser-window>
    <code-block language="html" label="Heading hierarchy">{{ hierarchyCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <p><strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> Each page should have exactly one <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code>. Sections use <code>&lt;h2&gt;</code>. Subsections use <code>&lt;h3&gt;</code>. Levels 4&ndash;6 are for fine-grained structure within long documents.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Heading Links</h2>
    <p>Wrap content in the <a href="/docs/elements/web-components/heading-links/"><code>&lt;heading-links&gt;</code></a> web component to add hover-reveal anchor links to headings. It auto-generates <code>id</code> attributes from heading text and supports click-to-copy URL.</p>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/headings-with-links.html" url="https://vanilla-breeze.dev/headings/links" title="Heading links" shadow></browser-window>
    <code-block language="html" label="Heading links">{{ headingLinksCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <p>By default, <code>&lt;heading-links&gt;</code> processes <code>h2</code> and <code>h3</code>. Use <code>data-levels="h2,h3,h4"</code> to include additional levels.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Table of Contents</h2>
    <p>The <a href="/docs/elements/web-components/page-toc/"><code>&lt;page-toc&gt;</code></a> web component auto-generates a table of contents from headings with scroll-spy highlighting. It pairs with <code>&lt;heading-links&gt;</code> which provides the heading IDs.</p>

    <code-block language="html" label="Page table of contents">{{ pageTocCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <p>Both components default to <code>h2</code> and <code>h3</code> because <code>h1</code> is the page title (not a section) and <code>h4&ndash;h6</code> are too granular for most navigation.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Theme Ornament Hooks</h2>
    <p>Themes can add decorative glyphs before or after headings using CSS custom properties. These tokens are theme-controlled &mdash; the base VB stylesheet sets them to <code>none</code>.</p>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/headings-ornaments.html" url="https://vanilla-breeze.dev/headings/ornaments" title="Heading ornaments" shadow></browser-window>
    <code-block language="css" label="Theme ornament tokens">{{ ornamentCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Token</th>
          <th>Scope</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--heading-ornament-before</code></td>
          <td>All headings (h1&ndash;h6)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--heading-ornament-after</code></td>
          <td>All headings (h1&ndash;h6)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--h1-ornament-before</code> / <code>after</code></td>
          <td>h1 only (overrides global)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--h2-ornament-before</code> / <code>after</code></td>
          <td>h2 only (overrides global)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--h3-ornament-before</code> / <code>after</code></td>
          <td>h3 only (overrides global)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Typography Features</h2>
    <p>Headings include several typographic refinements applied automatically:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong><code>font-variant-numeric: lining-nums</code></strong> &mdash; Numbers align with capital letters rather than descending like oldstyle numerals</li>
      <li><strong><code>hyphens: none</code></strong> &mdash; Headings are never hyphenated, even when the parent has <code>hyphens: auto</code></li>
      <li><strong><code>text-wrap: balance</code></strong> &mdash; Text distributes evenly across lines, preventing short orphan lines</li>
      <li><strong><code>letter-spacing</code></strong> &mdash; h1 and h2 get tighter tracking at large sizes for better visual density</li>
    </ul>

    <code-block language="css" label="Heading CSS">{{ cssCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Heading Groups</h2>
    <p>Use <a href="/docs/elements/native/hgroup/"><code>&lt;hgroup&gt;</code></a> to pair a heading with a subtitle, eyebrow label, byline, or other secondary text. Only the heading contributes to the document outline.</p>

    <code-block language="html" label="Heading group">{{ hgroupCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <p>See the <a href="/docs/elements/native/hgroup/">hgroup documentation</a> for all variants including <code>.eyebrow</code>, <code>.byline</code>, <code>.section-header</code>, and <code>.display</code>.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>One h1 per page</strong> &mdash; The page title. Screen readers use it as the primary landmark</li>
      <li><strong>Sequential levels</strong> &mdash; Never skip levels (h1 &rarr; h3). Screen reader users navigate by heading level</li>
      <li><strong>Descriptive text</strong> &mdash; Headings should summarize the section content. Avoid generic text like "Section 1"</li>
      <li><strong>Don't use for styling</strong> &mdash; Choose heading level by hierarchy, not visual size. Use CSS to adjust appearance</li>
      <li><strong>heading-links</strong> &mdash; The anchor links added by <code>&lt;heading-links&gt;</code> include descriptive <code>aria-label</code> attributes</li>
      <li><strong>Heading count</strong> &mdash; Screen readers can list all headings on a page. Well-structured headings serve as an alternative navigation method</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

